# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oak:unit-204
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Cold places: what is it like at the North and South Poles?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the North and South Poles through their locations, climates, landscapes, wildlife and ways of life. Pupils learn to compare the Arctic and Antarctic using maps, images and geographical vocabulary to describe features of cold environments."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of extreme environments by applying their knowledge of weather, seasonal change and global geography. Its placement allows for direct comparison of polar regions and builds the foundation for future learning about climate, habitats and adaptation.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should have experience of measuring temperature, know that the sun’s energy heats Earth and that there are seasonal variations.
Know that Earth orbits the sun once a year.
Pupils should have had experience of noticing, measuring, and talking about weather features including temperature, rainfall, snow and ice.""" ;
  curric:id "204"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.343942Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-203
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Life in a capital city: London/Cardiff"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the capital cities of London and Cardiff through their landmarks, transport, rivers and green spaces. Pupils describe key physical and human features and plan a day out using maps, images and simple route planning."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ understanding of the UK’s nations and capital cities by focusing in depth on two contrasting urban locations. Its placement supports the development of locational knowledge, place comparison and urban geography through applied geographical skills.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should know that the UK is made up of England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
Pupils are able to locate England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland using an atlas or map.
Pupils know that each of these countries of the UK has its own capital and that London is the capital of both England and the UK.""" ;
  curric:id "203"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.417175Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-the-uk-and-regions .

oak:unit-207
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Contrasting locality: what is it like to live in Jamaica/Tanzania?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores what it is like to live in a contrasting locality by studying Jamaica and Tanzania. Pupils investigate location, climate, and key physical and human features, and compare each place with their own through maps, images and geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces a contrasting non-European locality, as required by the National Curriculum, and builds on pupils’ understanding of their own place. Its placement supports meaningful comparison, encouraging empathy, curiosity and awareness of diverse ways of living.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of global geography and the use of a globe to locate places.
Knowledge of the local area.
Some knowledge of using Google Earth, aerial photographs, map, stories and other source of geographical information to investigate places.""" ;
  curric:id "207"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.419832Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-americas-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-202
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The UK: what kind of place is it?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces the United Kingdom as a country made up of four nations. Pupils learn to name and locate the nations, capital cities and surrounding seas, and explore distinctive geographical features across the UK using maps and images."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces national-scale geography through a focused study of the UK, including its countries, capitals and surrounding seas, as outlined in the National Curriculum. Its placement builds on pupils’ locational knowledge and prepares them for regional comparisons in later units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some experience of locating and mapping their local area, naming basic geographical features and using maps at this scale.
A basic understanding of the world as a framework of continents and countries and oceans.""" ;
  curric:id "202"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.421440Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-water-and-rivers ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-the-uk-and-regions ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

oak:unit-205
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Hot places: where are they and what are they like?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the world’s hottest places, focusing on tropical rainforests and hot deserts. Pupils use maps and images to locate these environments, describe their climates and features, and compare contrasting hot places around the world."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ understanding of weather, seasonal change and polar regions by introducing contrasting hot environments. Its placement supports comparison across climate zones and prepares pupils for future learning about biomes, vegetation and human-environment interaction.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should know the difference between hot and cold temperatures.
They should know that the Polar Areas are cold places.
They should know the location of the Poles and the Equator.""" ;
  curric:id "205"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.479288Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-206
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: why is (our place) special?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores what makes the local area special by identifying key features, landmarks and places of interest. Pupils use maps, address and direction language, local climate knowledge and fieldwork to describe and represent their locality."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit consolidates pupils’ geographical understanding by revisiting their local area through enriched knowledge of features, mapping and place significance. Positioned at the end of Year 2, it prepares pupils to make meaningful comparisons with other places in future study.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Knowledge of the locality including school, home and the local area, including through fieldwork.
Some experience of using simple mapping techniques to locate and annotate places.""" ;
  curric:id "206"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.498401Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-local-area .

oak:unit-275
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local to global: how can we identify special places?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores what makes places special by combining personal geography with global examples. Pupils describe, annotate and locate familiar places before learning about the natural and human wonders of the world using images, maps and geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit draws together the year’s learning by linking pupils’ personal experiences of place with global examples of significance. Its position at the end of Year 1 helps pupils reflect on their growing spatial awareness and prepares them to compare places in Year 2.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of the local area through first-hand experience.some experience of using aerial photographs, maps and plans of the school grounds, of fieldwork, and of making models and maps.
Some knowledge of the local area through first-hand experience.
Some experience of using aerial photographs, maps and plans of the school grounds, of fieldwork, and of making models and maps.""" ;
  curric:id "275"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.510703Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-diversity ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-272
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Continents and oceans: what can we find out about the world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit uses globes, maps and satellite images to explore the world’s continents, oceans, rivers and mountains. Pupils locate key features and landmarks and begin to understand the UK’s position in the wider world."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to geography at the global scale, building on their earlier studies of the school and local area. Its placement supports progression in scale, helping pupils understand how their locality and the UK fit within the wider world. Pupils develop spatial awareness through engagement with photographs, satellite images and maps, supporting early understanding of spatial relationships and nested hierarchies. This foundation prepares pupils for future comparative and thematic studies.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some awareness of the wider world through stories and other media and some experience of globes and maps.""" ;
  curric:id "272"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.567400Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-diversity ,
    oak:thread-interconnection .

oak:unit-274
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: how do we read maps and plan routes?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of maps and route planning by exploring their school grounds. Pupils create maps, use symbols and keys, plan and follow routes, and apply their knowledge through simple fieldwork and observation."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on prior learning about the school and local area by developing pupils’ ability to represent and navigate space. Its placement enables the introduction of early mapping conventions and supports future units that involve route descriptions and spatial comparisons.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of the local area through first-hand experience.
Some experience of using aerial photographs, maps and plans of the school grounds.
Some experience of fieldwork, and of making models and maps.""" ;
  curric:id "274"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.580262Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-local-area .

oak:unit-273
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Seasons: how does the weather change through the year?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces weather and seasonal change by exploring different types of weather and how they vary across the year. Pupils observe and measure the weather, identify patterns, and begin to relate seasonal change to the calendar year."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ existing awareness of the seasons, using this lived experience to introduce weather and seasonal change as geographical patterns. Its placement supports progression from local place knowledge and prepares pupils for later studies of climate and biomes.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Opportunities to talk about and name weather elements and notice seasonal change.
Experience of recording some simple weather data.""" ;
  curric:id "273"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.580774Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-climate-and-weather ,
    oak:thread-earth-geometry ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes .

oak:unit-270
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: where do we go to school?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Explore the school environment to identify features, describe locations using simple vocabulary, interpret aerial photos and observe seasonal change through early fieldwork."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to the concept of place by using their immediate surroundings to begin developing spatial awareness. Positioned at the very start of the geography curriculum, it establishes key vocabulary and observational skills that will support later learning about other familiar and contrasting locations. Focusing on the school grounds enables pupils to practise describing features and locations at a scale that is meaningful and accessible.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of the local area through first-hand experience.
Some experience of using aerial photographs, maps and plans of the school grounds.
Some experience of fieldwork and of making models and maps.""" ;
  curric:id "270"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.627381Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-local-area .

oak:unit-271
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Local area: where do we live?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit investigates the area around school and home by identifying local features, exploring buildings, using simple maps, collecting data on how we travel to school, and describing familiar routes using basic geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils’ earlier study of their school by extending their understanding of place to the wider local area. Its placement enables pupils to begin working with simple maps, using familiar locations to develop early mapping skills such as identifying features and interpreting symbols. By exploring geography at a slightly broader scale, this unit supports progression toward comparing distant places later in the curriculum and lays a foundation for more complex spatial thinking.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Some knowledge of the local area through first-hand experience.
Some experience of using aerial photographs, maps and plans of the school grounds.
Some experience of fieldwork and of making models and maps.""" ;
  curric:id "271"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.659346Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf eng:scheme-geography-key-stage-1 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-land-use-and-settlement ,
    oak:thread-economic-activity ,
    oak:thread-natural-resources ,
    oak:thread-local-area ,
    oak:thread-human-processes ,
    oak:thread-physical-processes ,
    oak:thread-diversity .

