oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2583-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People first went to the Southern Ocean and Antarctica hunting for whales, then explorers raced to the South Pole."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.482954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2583-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Antarctic Treaty is there to protect the continent and states no one country can claim it as its own."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.482960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2583-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There is no permanent population in Antarctica but scientists and tourists visit the continent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.482990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2575-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many different ways to travel to London such as long distance trains, or national and international flights."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606345Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2575-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Travel guides can help you decide where you want to go when you are visiting a new place, like London."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606352Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2575-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Once in London, maps and travel tools can help you identify the best routes to get to where you need to go."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606360Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2575-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Locating the landmarks and places you want to visit will help you map the best route to see as many of them as possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2599-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "People go on holiday for different reasons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2599-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Tourists visit Jamaica for its climate and geographical features."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607043Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2599-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Tourism affects places in different ways; some of these effects can be good and some can be bad."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2566-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scotland is mountainous in the north and west, and flatter in the south and east."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608357Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2566-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most people in Scotland live in the bigger towns and cities in the flatter areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2566-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The countryside in Scotland has smaller towns and villages, farmland, forests and lakes known as lochs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2566-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Scotland has a varied coastline and many islands."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2564-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The United Kingdom, called the UK for short, is a country that is part of the continent of Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2564-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The UK consists of a large island, part of another island and many smaller islands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616566Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2564-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The UK is separated from Europe by the North Sea and English Channel, and from Ireland by the Irish Sea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2565-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The UK is made up of four countries: England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2565-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A capital city is the place in a country where the government ‘sits’ and has its centre of power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2565-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Belfast, Cardiff, Edinburgh and London are capitals of NI, Wales, Scotland and England; London is also capital of UK."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2586-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The largest hot desert in the world is the Sahara, in North Africa, and it is still growing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2586-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hot deserts have extremely high temperatures during the day and very little rain; not much life can survive there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2586-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Not many people live in hot desert regions because of the lack of water for everyday activities and growing crops."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621107Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2592-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A landmark is a notable human or physical feature with meaning attached to it."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.624204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2592-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Landmarks can be personal to you, known locally, or of national or global importance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.624209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2592-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Landmarks can be human features such as a statue or building e.g. Buckingham palace, the Taj Mahal, Hadrian's Wall."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.624214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2592-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Landmarks can be physical features e.g. Giant's Causeway (Northern Ireland), Sycamore Gap (England), Yr Wyddfa (Wales)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.624220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3179-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use images and maps to investigate places, e.g. the ‘Seven wonders of the natural world’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.626639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3179-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Geographers sometimes add labels or captions to images to share their opinions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.626644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3179-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Surveys help geographers find out what people do or think, e.g. what is their favourite natural wonder?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.626649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2584-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sun’s energy is more concentrated when it is directly overhead: in the tropics this happens throughout the year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.646661Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2584-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The tropics are areas either side of the equator where the sun remains high in the sky throughout the year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.646666Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2584-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Places that are hot and wet all year round are found at the Equator."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.646671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2584-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hot and dry areas called hot deserts can be found on the northern and southern edges of the tropical region."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.646676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2593-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can use a fieldwork safety code to stay safe when completing fieldwork."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2593-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As well as gathering facts about places, a sense of place can be developed using the senses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647006Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2593-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Interesting and favourite human and physical features can be shared with trails, maps and guides for visitors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2593-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fieldwork helps us collect information about a place using first-hand experience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647015Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2579-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Antarctic Circle is an imagined circle around the South Pole that surrounds the area known as the Antarctic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647111Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2579-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Antarctica is a large region, surrounded by the Southern Ocean, and is the coldest and windiest continent on Earth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2579-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some of Antarctica’s Ice Cap is more than four kilometres thick."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2579-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Antarctica can double in size by the end of the Antarctic winter as the sea ice around the continent increases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6817-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between places and the lives of people in different parts of the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647518Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6817-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Photographs can be used to investigate and compare Arusha and my local area."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6817-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between the physical and human features in Arusha and my own local area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.647528Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2573-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Green spaces and trees help soak up noise and pollution from traffic and provide peaceful spots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2573-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Nearly one fifth of London is covered by around 3000 parks and green spaces."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2573-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "London was declared the world’s first National Park City in 2019."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6671-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Mountains are areas of land that are much higher than the land around them."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653442Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6671-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A group of mountains in one area is called a mountain range, and there are mountain ranges on every continent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6671-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Every continent has some special places and landmarks."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6671-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some of the natural features in the world, such as the Grand Canyon in North America, are called landmarks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653460Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6671-5
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are some built features that are amazing too, such as the Pyramids in Egypt and the Taj Mahal in India."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.653465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3170-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An imaginary scenario can help us to plan what we would show an alien visiting our school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3170-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Routes can be plotted on large-scale maps and aerial photographs of familiar places, e.g. the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3170-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographical vocabulary is used to name and describe familiar places, e.g. features of the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3167-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is summer in the UK in June, July and August."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3167-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Summer is the hottest time of the year and has the most hours of daylight."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3167-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can see signs of summer by observing weather, plants and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3167-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can make and compare seasonal maps of the school grounds to help us talk about changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.654387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3168-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In the UK, spring falls in the months of March, April and May."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657664Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3168-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In spring, the days start to get warmer and there are more hours of daylight."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3168-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can see signs of spring by observing the weather, plants and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3168-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can make and compare seasonal maps of the school grounds to help us talk about changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657678Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3149-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Photographs can give clues about the location where they were taken."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3149-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use locational language to describe where things are e.g. the location of a toy in the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3149-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers can record places on an aerial photograph e.g. the location of a toy in the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657692Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3149-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers can follow or record a route on a map; large scale maps are best for small areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6819-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Daily life in Arusha can be investigated using pictures and written sources of information."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6819-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many ways in which our lives are the same as, but also different from, other people’s lives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6819-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between a child’s life in Arusha and my own life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.657716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3180-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Human as well as natural features can be special, e.g. the Riverside Museum in Glasgow."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3180-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Geographers use images and maps to investigate places, e.g. landmarks."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3180-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers sometimes add labels or captions to images and maps to share their opinions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3180-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers make models and maps to share their ideas about places, including imagined buildings or places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3173-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "‘Journey sticks’ help us remember what we saw during a fieldtrip."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.661804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3173-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Sequencing photographs helps recall of a journey and places visited."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.661809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3173-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Geographers make maps to show what places are like and to show routes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.661813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3173-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Models or maps made from memory are not usually very accurate, but show what is important to the maker."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.661818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6816-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Google Earth can be used to locate places in Tanzania."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6816-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are many different human and physical features in Tanzania."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6816-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Google Earth can be used to investigate Tanzania’s human and physical features."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2596-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Human features are things that are made by people and physical features occur naturally."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664360Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2596-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial photographs and satellite images are useful for finding out about Jamaica."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2596-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial photographs and satellite images can be labelled to show physical and human features."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.664369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3155-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In investigations, geographers collect and organise information to sort and rank it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.665631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3155-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many different means of transport are used to travel to school, e.g. bus, walk, car, train, bike."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.665636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3155-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Graphs showing information (or data) from fieldwork or surveys can help us discuss and analyse what has been found out."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.665640Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3155-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People have different reasons for choosing how they travel, e.g. distance, time available, safety, the weather, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.665645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6814-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Africa is a very large continent with different climates, countries and landscapes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6814-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The compass directions north, south, west and east can be used to describe the location of places in Africa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667170Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6814-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can take different routes and types of transport to get to Tanzania from the UK."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3174-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """School grounds can be adapted and changed to provide spaces and features that pupils want."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3174-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A birds eye perspective is what a seagull might see if it flew overhead."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3174-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers make models and maps to share ideas, information and opinions about places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667188Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3151-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial images and large-scale maps can be used to find and identify our homes and other familiar features."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3151-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Locational vocabulary is used to describe the location of our homes and other local features."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3151-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are different types of homes: terraced/semi-detached/detached houses, flats, bungalows, cottages, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.667202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2572-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The River Thames was one of the earliest transport routes: people travelled up and down the river in boats for trade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.668536Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2572-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """London is famous for its red double decker buses, black taxi cabs and its London Underground tube trains."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.668541Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2572-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are special rules to help keep the most polluting cars out of central London."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.668545Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2572-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To reduce pollution, a network of bicycles and electric scooters are available to hire in London."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.668552Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3163-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The weather describes the conditions of the outside world at any one time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673263Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3163-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The wind direction is the direction that the wind is coming from: a north wind blows from the north."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673267Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3163-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The temperature is a measure of how hot or cold it is."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3163-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fresh water that falls to the ground from clouds can take different forms, such as rain, snow, hail or sleet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673276Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-9357-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is autumn in the UK in September, October and November."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673280Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-9357-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In autumn, the days start to get colder and there are fewer hours of daylight."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673287Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-9357-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can see signs of autumn by observing the weather, plants and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-9357-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can make and compare seasonal maps of the school grounds to help us talk about changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.673297Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3152-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most local areas include geographical features such as houses, shops, places of worship and green spaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.674031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3152-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Digital maps can switch from aerial to map view to help identify the familiar features of the local area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.674036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3152-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Locational language, maps, aerial images and fieldwork are used to identify and locate features in the local area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.674040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6798-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The River Taff flows from the north to the south of the city and drains into Cardiff Bay, a freshwater lake."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6798-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Over 200 years ago, a famous engineer called Isambard Kingdom Brunel changed the course of the River Taff."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6798-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff Station was then built in an area that used to flood before the river was diverted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6798-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The River Taff used to be heavily polluted but is now home to trout, salmon and other wildlife."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3161-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Rivers carry water from high places such as mountains to a sea, ocean or lake."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3161-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are rivers on every continent, and some of the biggest rivers are the Nile and the Amazon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.678959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2567-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "England is mountainous in the north and west, and flatter in the south and east."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2567-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most people in the UK live in England; there are lots of cities, towns and villages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2567-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The countryside in England has smaller towns and villages, farmland, forests, lakes and moorland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679891Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2567-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "England's coastline has many sandy beaches."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679895Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2578-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Arctic Circle is an imagined circle around the North Pole that surrounds the area known as the Arctic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2578-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Much of the Artic Ocean around the North Pole is frozen sea ice, two to three metres thick, but this reduces in summer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2578-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The northern edges of three continents: North America, Europe and Asia, can be found within the Arctic Circle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2578-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Arctic Summer has almost continuous daylight and the winter almost continuous darkness."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.679914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3166-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is winter in the UK in December, January and February."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3166-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Winter is the coldest time of the year and has the fewest hours of daylight."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3166-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can see signs of winter by observing the weather, plants and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3166-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can make and compare seasonal maps of the school grounds to help us talk about changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6815-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Photographs can be used to investigate the geography of Tanzania."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.682416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6815-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Tanzania has a warm climate that varies across the country."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.682420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6815-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are a range of landscapes in Tanzania."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.682425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3146-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial photographs help us identify the main features of a school and its surroundings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3146-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers go outside to gather information in different ways and we call this fieldwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3146-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use photographs and sketches with labels to share opinions, information and ideas about places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3146-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use locational vocabulary to describe where things are. E.g., the location of familiar features in the school ground."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6672-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Continents are divided into smaller areas known as countries."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6672-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The UK is a country located in Europe with the Atlantic Ocean to its west."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6672-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We may have friends and family who live in other countries in the world."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6672-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We can locate the UK on a globe and our location in the UK on a map."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3176-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A favourite visited place may be nearby, or far away, even in another country."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3176-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Geographical vocabulary helps us talk about why places are special to us."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687422Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3176-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers make connections between what a place is like and the activities that are possible there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3176-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "All places can be located using maps and globes or atlases."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.687431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2598-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Different crops are suited to different climates."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2598-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Questions are a useful way to learn more about farming in Jamaica."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689253Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2598-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We are connected to different countries by the food we eat."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689257Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2598-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Bananas, sugar, yams, peppers, tomatoes and peas all grow in Jamaica."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2571-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A capital city is where a country's government has its headquarters and where it makes important decisions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2571-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many people commute to London for work and millions of tourists visit or travel through the city."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2571-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """London has many important buildings and landmarks, such as Buckingham Palace, the Elizabeth Tower and Big Ben."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2569-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The highest mountain in Northern Ireland is Slieve Donard in the Mourne mountains to the south east."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689587Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2569-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most people in Northern Ireland live in Belfast, Northern Ireland's Capital and biggest city."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2569-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The countryside in Northern Ireland has small towns and villages, farms, forests and the UK's largest lake, Lough Neagh."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689597Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2569-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Northern Ireland has some incredible coastal features, e.g. Giant's Causeway."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.689601Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3158-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is hard to make a 2D map of a 3D world and so maps of the world can look quite different from each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3158-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We call large blocks of land continents and there are seven of these on Earth."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690207Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3158-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are seven continents: Europe, Africa, North America, South America, Asia, Oceania and Antarctica."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690212Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3158-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some continents, such as North and South America, are connected and some, such as Oceania, include lots of islands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3165-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We have seasons because Earth is tilted on its axis as it orbits the Sun each year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690221Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3165-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Each season has its own weather patterns and we can use weather data to talk about this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3165-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the North Pole is tilted away from the Sun, UK days have fewer hours of daylight, are colder, and it’s winter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3165-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the North Pole is tilted towards the Sun, UK days have more hours of daylight, are warmer, and it’s summer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.690237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3160-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ocean is a vast joined-up area of salt water covering nearly three-quarters of Earth's surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.691032Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3160-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We have five named ocean areas: Pacific, Atlantic, Indian, Arctic and Southern."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.691037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3160-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Oceans are very important for all life on Earth."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.691044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3171-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Maps of different scales, or a zoom function on a digital map, may be needed to locate pupils’ favourite play places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3171-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial photographs and large-scale maps show local features, including play areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3171-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Aerial photographs and large-scale maps can be used to plan routes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3171-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Play areas need to be accessed safely so thinking about routes and access is important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692595Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3169-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "We all have opinions on our favourite places to play around school."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692600Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3169-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial images and large-scale maps show the main features of a place, e.g. the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3169-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use images, words and maps to help them explain why they like a place and how they use it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.692609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6808-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Green spaces and trees help soak up noise and pollution too from traffic and provide peaceful spots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6808-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps help us to identify and name green spaces as well as other features."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6808-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Bute Park is a large park located behind Cardiff Castle and close to the shops, and the River Taff flows through it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3172-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Routes, e.g. to a local play area, can be plotted and followed on different kinds of maps."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3172-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use maps in fieldwork to find and locate specific features, e.g. in a local play area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3172-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use different ways of assessing features and places, such as when comparing views about a play area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3172-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Journey sticks can help us record and remember what a place is like."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3153-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers sometimes draw maps from memory, e.g. a map showing things in a street outside school."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3153-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers investigate places by going outside to gather information in different ways and we call this fieldwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3153-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Risk assessment means thinking about possible dangers and how you can keep yourself safe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3164-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A thermometer measures how hot or cold the air is and the reading can be affected by the time of day or season."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3164-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can measure rainfall using a gauge or count the number of rainy days within a given time, such as a week."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3164-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A weather vane uses compass directions to show where the wind is coming from."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693708Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3164-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We can build up a better picture of the weather pattern by taking weather readings at the same time and place each day."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.693716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3145-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Each school has a name that tells it apart from others."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.695290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3145-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are names for the different school buildings and parts of the grounds such as playground, field, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.695295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3145-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The address of the school includes its name, the road, the suburb or village and possibly a town or city."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.695299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3145-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps and addresses tell us where a place is located."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.695304Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6796-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A capital city is where the Government has their headquarters and makes important decisions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.702861Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6796-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Welsh name for Cardiff is Caerdydd; the Welsh language is widely spoken in Wales."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.702865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6796-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff Castle is on a site that is nearly 2000 years old and is an important landmark and tourist attraction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.702870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6796-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff grew into a large settlement very quickly because it was an important centre for the coal industry."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.702874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3157-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The round Earth is covered with water and land, and above that is the atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.703771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3157-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use models, called globes, and photographs taken from space to think about what the world is like."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.703776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3157-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most of the surface of the world (over 70%) is covered with water, which is why Earth is known as the Blue Planet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.703780Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3157-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The colours on a globe or satellite image give us information, such as whether it’s land or ocean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.703785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2594-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps can be used to locate the Caribbean Sea and the countries there."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2594-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Compass directions (north, east, south and west) can be used to describe the location of Caribbean countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2594-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The UK and Caribbean are connected in many different ways."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6818-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "People around the world do many different jobs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6818-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Arusha’s climate and geographical features affect some of the jobs that people do there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6818-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Talking to people is one way of finding out about what a place is like."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.704879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3147-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People may have similar and different ideas about the most important feature of a place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3147-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Real and relevant questions from people help geographers find out what others want to know about a place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3147-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers add captions or labels to photographs to share information and opinions about places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3147-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers might talk about the evidence they have collected to find out what others think."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705100Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2585-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Places close to the Equator have a hot and wet climate which are perfect conditions for tropical rainforests."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2585-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Temperatures in the Tropics temperatures reach over 24° Celsius every day of the year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2585-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Tropical rainforests support a great diversity of plants and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2585-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Fruit such as pineapples, bananas and mangoes grow well in tropical regions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705493Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3148-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are lots of different jobs in a primary school and some are easily noticed but others are not obvious."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3148-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Interviews are a good way of finding out information from people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3148-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Interviews need to be planned in advance, to ensure the right questions are asked."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705708Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3148-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Interviews can be recorded to help us remember what the person being interviewed said."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.705713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3154-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many streets include a range of buildings, including homes, shops, places of worship, offices, etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706821Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3154-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When doing fieldwork geographers use large-scale maps to locate their position and features they see."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3154-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers use maps, labels and photographs to share information about places they have investigated through fieldwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3175-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "People have different points of view about what makes a place special."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3175-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Places have features that can be named and described, and places also trigger different kinds of feelings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706842Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3175-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps can be annotated using a range of symbols including emoji symbols."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706847Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3175-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If geographers draw  maps of their special places, they will show similarities and differences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.706851Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2580-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Animals like polar bears live within the Arctic Circle and have special features to live in this environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707901Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2580-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Polar bears hibernate during the harsh Arctic winter and emerge during the summer months to hunt seals from the ice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2580-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Changing ice cover due to climate change means that some polar bear habitats are under threat."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2580-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Arctic ice is usually greatest in March after winter and least in September after the summer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6795-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial imagery and maps at different scales help us describe where places are using geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6795-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff is located in the south east of Wales, near the coast and close to the M4 motorway."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6795-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Cardiff is the largest city and capital city of Wales."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.707928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2589-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps and fieldwork can help us identify key features and where they are."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715695Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2589-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Marshes are low-lying, wet places near rivers and coasts, that often flood, and they attract a range of wildlife."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2589-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People do lots of different jobs: some need to be done wherever you live and some are unique to a locality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2588-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Places can be located using their address and postcode."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2588-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Maps and keys help us locate places, give directions and plan journeys."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2588-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Changing the scale on a map by zooming in or out shows us different views of a place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2588-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Public transport such as buses, trains and planes, are shared means of travel."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2568-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wales is very mountainous, its highest mountain is Yr Wyddfa (Snowdon) in North Wales."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.717576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2568-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The biggest cities in Wales are in the south."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.717581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2568-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The countryside in Wales has smaller towns and villages, farmland, forests, lakes and moorland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.717585Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2568-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Wales has a varied coastline with some major ports."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.717590Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2591-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A long-term pattern of weather is called climate and this can vary within the UK."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.719374Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2591-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The climate of the UK shows the south-east and some parts of the south-west, get most sunshine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.719378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2591-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The climate of the UK shows the north-west and mountainous areas get the least sunshine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.719383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2591-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A meteorologist is someone who investigates and measures weather and climate, and makes predictions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.719387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2595-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A range of resources can be used to investigate the location, climate and features of Jamaica."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2595-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Tropical weather and climate have an impact on the environment and daily life."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720422Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2595-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hurricanes are a type of storm with very strong winds and heavy rain; they can cause a lot of damage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2597-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Digital maps and aerial photographs are useful for finding out about the human features in Kingston."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2597-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are different types of settlement in Jamaica."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720435Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2597-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between Kingston and the place where I live."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.720440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3150-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Recording daily weather conditions (e.g. temperature, wind direction and speed) develops weather-specific vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723142Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3150-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are four seasons, and signs of each of them can be seen in the school grounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723147Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3150-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fieldwork outside, e.g. finding signs of autumn, develops geographical vocabulary, observation and recording skills."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3150-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geographers take photographs, draw pictures, make models, or add information to maps to record what they notice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723155Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2577-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The geographical North and South Poles mark where Earth’s axis meets Earth’s surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2577-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The North Pole is located in the Arctic Ocean and the South Pole in the frozen continent of Antarctica."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723740Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2577-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Antarctic is colder because of its land mass, with high mountains and the Arctic warmer because much is ocean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2577-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ice sheets cover land and ice shelves extend over the ocean."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.723749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2576-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Locally, air temperatures are affected by factors such wind direction and speed, shelter and shade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.728746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2576-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Globally, as Earth orbits the sun, temperatures are affected by where a place is and time of year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.728751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2576-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the Northern Hemisphere winter, the North Pole is tilted away from the sun and is darker and colder as a result."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.728755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2576-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While places in the Northern Hemisphere experience winter, the opposite happens in the Southern Hemisphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.728761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2590-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The 'local area' can mean different things to different people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2590-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Maps can be used to plot and show your typical range and places visited in a week, and how you feel about them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731844Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2590-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A typical local range will probably include your school, your house, the local shops and play areas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3156-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Geographers make maps to show journeys, e.g. their route to school."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3156-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Map-makers use symbols and colours to show information and sometimes maps need a key."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3156-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The routes most walked or travelled may show the same buildings and landmarks."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2574-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People settled by the River Thames for navigation, trade and a water supply. Today, many bridges connect both banks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2574-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Today, Londoners use the most water in the country; much of this comes from the River Thames."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738217Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2574-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Waste water is also pumped into the River Thames, which is why a new super sewer is being built."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738221Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2574-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Thames’ Barrier is a special piece of engineering that is designed to protect London from flooding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738225Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2570-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aerial imagery and maps at different scales help us describe where places are using geographical vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2570-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """London is a city near the mouth of the River Thames in the south-east of England and the UK."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740332Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2570-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "London is the capital and largest city of the UK."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740336Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2582-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greenland is the largest non-continent island in the world, and nearly 80,000 people live there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.741622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2582-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greenland is part of the Kingdom of Denmark, in Europe, but is geographically part of the North America continent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.741626Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2582-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Because Greenlanders need to live by the coast, fishing is important. Fish and seal are the main catches."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.741630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2582-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Houses are often made from stone, concrete and corrugated metal as few trees grow there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.741634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2581-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "All the creatures that come to the Antarctic feed in the sea."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.744463Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2581-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Penguins are only found in the Southern Hemisphere."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.744467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2581-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many species of penguin visit the Antarctic during the summer because of the abundant food and hours of daylight."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.744473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2581-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Emperor Penguin is the only species of penguin that remains in the Antarctic throughout the winter months."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.744477Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6809-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many different ways to travel to Cardiff such as long distance trains, or national and international flights."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6809-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Travel guides can help you decide where you want to go when you are visiting a new place, like Cardiff."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6809-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Locating the landmarks and places you want to visit will help you map the best route for seeing as many as possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6809-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Once in Cardiff, maps and travel tools can help you identify the best routes to get to where you need to go."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2587-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many people leave the UK when they go on holiday to seek sunshine and warmth, especially during the winter months."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2587-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The right clothes and equipment can help protect us from extreme heat and cold."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749258Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2587-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many homes and offices in hot climates have air conditioning installed, although this uses a lot of energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749262Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-2587-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The hot and wet areas of the world also attract insects like mosquitoes that might sting or bite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6797-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff Central railway station is the largest railway station in Wales, used by millions of passengers each year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749859Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6797-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Cardiff is home to the only international airport in Wales."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6797-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cardiff can be reached by car from England on the M4 motorway, though this is a very busy route."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6797-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An Aquabus water taxi runs from the city centre to Cardiff Bay and from there to Penarth, a nearby town."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-6797-5
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Taff Trail is a mainly traffic-free route from Cardiff to Brecon Beacons National Park that can be walked or cycled."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

